gw.api.system

Class PLConfigParameters

  • java.lang.Object
    • gw.api.system.PLConfigParameters

  • public class PLConfigParameters
extends Object
    Used to fetch the values of configuration parameters defined in config.xml The list of parameters here is the list of all legal config parameters.

      static StringParameterKey ClusterMulticastAddress
      The IP multicast address used to communicate with the other members of the cluster. Must be unique within the range of the cache time to live parameter. It is referenced in the protocol stack as multicastAddress.
      static IntegerParameterKey ClusterMulticastPort
      The port used to communicate with other members of the cluster. It is referenced in the protocol stack as port.
      static IntegerParameterKey ClusterMulticastTTL
      The time to live for cluster multicast packets.. For Guidewire the value will nearly always be 1, meaning only deliver the packets to the local subnet. Higher time to live values require multicast routing to be enabled on any intermediate routers (rare in most IT organizations). Also the larger the time to live the more you have to worry about allocating unique multicast addresses. It is referenced in the protocol stack as timeToLive.
      static StringParameterKey ClusterProtocolStack
      The cluster protocol stack string.
      static StringParameterKey ClusterProtocolStackOption1
      This is a local option that can contain other parameters for the ClusterProtocolStack, it is referenced in the stack as ${option1}. This is configured in the default protocol stack in the UDP protocol and can be set to ';bind_addr=xyz', so that a multihome server can specify which nic JGroups should use. Note that the string is a literal substitition which requires that it start with the ';' UDP parameter delimiter. See the JGroups documentation for other values that can also be assigned.
      static StringParameterKey ClusterProtocolStackOption2

      static IntegerParameterKey GlobalCacheActiveTimeMinutes
      Time period (in minutes) when cached items are considered "active", i.e. the cache should give higher priority to preserve these items. This can be thought of as the period when items are being heavily used, e.g. how long a user stays on a page. It should be less than the reaping time.
      static BooleanParameterKey GlobalCacheDetailedStats
      This parameter determines whether or not detailed statistics should be collected. If "true", the reason for eviction is recorded and correlated with later misses. This data is preserved only for the duration of the statistics window (defined by GlobalCacheStatsWindowMinutes). This parameter does not affect the collection of basic statistics such as hit and miss ratio.
      static IntegerParameterKey GlobalCacheReapingTimeMinutes
      Time (in minutes) since last use before cached items are considered eligible for reaping. This can be thought of as the period during which an entity is most likely to be re-used.
      static IntegerParameterKey GlobalCacheSizeMegabytes

      The percentage of the heap to allocate to the global cache.

      static IntegerParameterKey GlobalCacheStatsRetentionPeriodDays
      This parameter denotes the period of time (in days), in addition to today, for how long statistics are preserved for historical comparison.
      static IntegerParameterKey GlobalCacheStatsWindowMinutes
      This parameter denotes a period of time (in minutes) and is used for two purposes: 1) how long to preserve the reason why an item was evicted, after the event occurred. When a cache miss occurs, the reason is looked up and reported in the CacheInfo page. 2) The period for which to display statistics on the chart on the CacheInfo page.

      static BooleanParameterKey LockPrimaryEntityDuringMessageHandling
      Issue pl-9001 dealt with a performance penalty for locking during message send processing. This lock also occurs when the message is acted upon in the UI or in a message reply plugin.. Normally this should not be an issue and the locking of primary entity first prevents deadlocks. However, some sites consider this not worth the penalty and have agree to insure that deadlocks don't occur (i.e., by either not locking message, or locking all message on the primary object before locking the primary object). If the message has no primary entity then this has no effect.

      True if data types should validate in "strict" mode. Differences between "strict" and "legacy" mode: Decimal values are not automatically rounded to the required scale. Callers are responsible for rounding as necessary. FieldValidator-based data type values must conform to the required format, at the persistence layer. In "legacy" mode, non-conforming values could be set at the persistence layer, bypassing checks that only exist in the UI. Numeric range restrictions are enforced at the persistence layer. In "legacy" mode, non-conforming values could be set at the persistence layer, bypassing checks that only exist in the UI.

      static BooleanParameterKey UseSafeBundleForWebServiceOperations
      The soap webservices bundle was setting ignore bean version conflicts, several people have pointed out that this is quite dangerous. So we have changed the default behavior, and added an annotation to get back to that behavior, however we do not want to disrupt current customer in a minor version upgrade so the new behavior is dependent on setting this to true.

      The default value is "false".

      • LockPrimaryEntityDuringMessageHandling

        BooleanParameterKey LockPrimaryEntityDuringMessageHandling
        Issue pl-9001 dealt with a performance penalty for locking during message send processing. This lock also occurs when the message is acted upon in the UI or in a message reply plugin.. Normally this should not be an issue and the locking of primary entity first prevents deadlocks. However, some sites consider this not worth the penalty and have agree to insure that deadlocks don't occur (i.e., by either not locking message, or locking all message on the primary object before locking the primary object). If the message has no primary entity then this has no effect.

      • StrictDataTypes

        BooleanParameterKey StrictDataTypes
        True if data types should validate in "strict" mode. Differences between "strict" and "legacy" mode:
        • Decimal values are not automatically rounded to the required scale. Callers are responsible for rounding as necessary.
        • FieldValidator-based data type values must conform to the required format, at the persistence layer. In "legacy" mode, non-conforming values could be set at the persistence layer, bypassing checks that only exist in the UI.
        • Numeric range restrictions are enforced at the persistence layer. In "legacy" mode, non-conforming values could be set at the persistence layer, bypassing checks that only exist in the UI.
